== Quintuplets

Generalizing swing to subdivision systems other than binary ones naturally
requires becoming familiar with odd subdivisions, such as triplets or
quintuplets. In this session, I propose that we focus specifically on
quintuplets.

=== Vocabulary of Patterns

When working with four subdivisions per beat (sixteenth notes over a
quarter-note pulse), we are used to thinking of rhythms as being built from a
small vocabulary of elementary patterns. In practice, any rhythmic line can be
described as a sequence of just six basic rhythmic "words" (or seven, if we
include the simple quarter note):

#figure(
  image("../Figures/voc4.png"),
)

Note that we deliberately exclude patterns that start with a rest. Unlike
silences occurring within the subdivision grid, a silence on the beat is almost
always perceived as a "loud silence": it functions perceptually as an onset,
not as an absence of sound.

We establish a similar vocabulary for the quintuplet subdivision:

#figure(
  image("../Figures/voc5.png"),
)

The idea is to practice each of these patterns (suggestion: keep the first two
for the end of the practice session) by using them as templates to articulate
musical phrases, improvise lines, or construct grooves. Within each pattern,
one can also explore variations of articulation, accentuation, and phrasing.